WEBVTT

00:00:10.100 --> 00:00:10.870
Good morning!

00:00:10.870 --> 00:00:13.600
I hope you all are
having a good day so far.

00:00:13.690 --> 00:00:15.760
Welcome to Publishing
with the iBookstore.

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:17.950
My name is Kristi Gillis.

00:00:18.070 --> 00:00:21.540
I've worked in publishing
for more than 10 years,

00:00:21.540 --> 00:00:25.740
and at Apple, my team manages worldwide
publisher support.

00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:29.140
It is absolutely a pleasure
to be with you guys this

00:00:29.230 --> 00:00:31.100
morning to talk about books.

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:35.370
Publishing with the iBookstore is
the first of five presentations

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:37.720
about books at this year's WWDC.

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:40.640
In the next hour,
we're going to focus on four

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:42.940
key areas of the book business.

00:00:42.940 --> 00:00:47.980
First, iBooks and what's technically
possible with books.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.140
Second, we're going to talk about how you
get started with the iBookstore.

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:55.640
Third, we'll talk about delivering
books to the bookstore.

00:00:56.230 --> 00:00:59.410
And what you can expect from
the book approval process.

00:00:59.410 --> 00:01:03.920
And finally, last but not least,
we're going to talk about how you market

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:05.750
your books and reach your readers.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:08.480
It's my hope that at
the end of this hour,

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:13.600
you're going to leave inspired by the
possibilities of books and determined

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:15.900
to become a bookseller with us.

00:01:16.700 --> 00:01:20.160
Because publishing is big business.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:25.900
In 2010, publishers based in the
United States grossed $27.9 billion.

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:32.730
Now, it used to be that to grab a piece
of this pie and to participate in

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:33.160
the publishing space required a
tremendous amount of fiscal investment.

00:01:33.220 --> 00:01:42.400
You needed to have a printing
press to print your books.

00:01:42.930 --> 00:01:45.520
And when your books were ready to go,
you needed to have some tractor

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:45.700
trailers to go and to pick them all up.

00:01:51.410 --> 00:01:58.330
Then, they needed to go to your
physical distribution center,

00:01:58.330 --> 00:01:58.330
so you needed to have a warehouse
to hold all of your books.

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:02.910
Then, when a customer placed an order,
you would need to have someone to pick,

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:05.930
pack, and ship those books.

00:02:06.310 --> 00:02:09.740
They need to get on another truck and
make their way across the country.

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:12.300
Sometimes they'd even
need to ride on a boat.

00:02:12.590 --> 00:02:16.440
And then they find their way
onto the shelves in a bookshop,

00:02:16.530 --> 00:02:19.520
where hopefully someone found them,
fell in love with them,

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:20.700
and took them home.

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:23.760
Because if not,
they could begin making their way

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:26.040
back to you as inventory returns.

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:29.870
They get back onto another truck,
and they come back to

00:02:29.910 --> 00:02:31.690
your distribution center.

00:02:31.690 --> 00:02:34.300
This is sort of the old way.

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:37.950
I'm very happy to say
that times have changed.

00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:43.840
Now to publish all you need
is a great idea and a Mac.

00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:47.390
The iBookstore ecosystem
begins with iBooks.

00:02:47.510 --> 00:02:51.460
iBooks is Apple's
revolutionary app for readers.

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:57.400
So it enables readers to look
at books that contain video,

00:02:57.930 --> 00:03:00.020
audio, and even interactivity.

00:03:00.020 --> 00:03:02.990
Readers are able to actually
work within the books themselves.

00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:08.140
iBooks also allows readers to design
their own libraries of content.

00:03:08.140 --> 00:03:10.620
And you can see here, here's my shelf.

00:03:10.780 --> 00:03:12.640
This is, I've named it Kristi's shelf.

00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:14.190
Pretty creative name.

00:03:14.190 --> 00:03:17.140
But if, like me,
maybe you want to put your cookbooks on

00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:20.260
one shelf and your novels on another,
you're able to do that.

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:26.480
You're able to build
collections of books.

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:26.500
And then as a reader,
when you need more content,

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:28.780
you simply click through the
app directly to the iBooks store

00:03:29.130 --> 00:03:32.580
where you can browse our holdings
and make additional purchases.

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:38.440
Now yesterday in the keynote address,
Tim shared with us that there are

00:03:38.440 --> 00:03:41.350
400 million App Store customers.

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:44.510
These are App Store customers
with credit cards on file.

00:03:44.510 --> 00:03:47.620
And what I'm delighted to say
this morning is that these are

00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:49.370
also iBooks store customers.

00:03:49.700 --> 00:03:52.330
These are readers who are here,
they're in the store,

00:03:52.330 --> 00:03:54.490
and they're waiting for your books.

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:56.480
So let's get into it.

00:03:56.500 --> 00:03:58.460
So let's get into how we reach them.

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:01.520
And to get us started,
we want to start with iBooks and

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:03.480
talk about the books themselves.

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:08.480
So to lead us in that discussion,
I'd like to introduce Al Canestraro,

00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:10.420
head of iBooks Engineering,
to tell us about books.

00:04:10.730 --> 00:04:12.290
Hi, everybody.

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:16.480
I'm the engineering manager for iBooks,
the application.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:21.590
We've been working really hard for the
last two years to make the most fully

00:04:21.730 --> 00:04:24.480
featured book reader on the planet.

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:26.460
And what I want to show you
today is a little bit of a story.

00:04:26.460 --> 00:04:28.710
What I want to show you today are
some of the ways that you can enhance

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:33.460
your book to make them stand out on
the iBooks store and make a great

00:04:33.460 --> 00:04:34.460
way for you to reach your customers.

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:37.460
So I want to show you three
different book types today.

00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:40.440
The first book type is
called a flowing book.

00:04:40.590 --> 00:04:42.460
And it's probably the one
you're most familiar with.

00:04:42.590 --> 00:04:46.680
It contains mostly text but
can be enhanced in ways that

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:49.140
were impossible with print.

00:04:49.750 --> 00:04:52.160
The second book type
is a fixed layout book.

00:04:52.230 --> 00:04:55.850
And those are perfect if you're starting
with a layout or you're starting with an

00:04:55.940 --> 00:04:57.850
aspect ratio that you need to respect.

00:04:58.210 --> 00:04:59.730
And it's backed by WebKit.

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:04.600
So you can do things like animations
and interaction and JavaScript,

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:07.510
which of course you can't do with print.

00:05:07.670 --> 00:05:11.400
And the last book type I'm going to show
you today is called a multi-touch book.

00:05:11.450 --> 00:05:15.600
And these are created with the
amazing iBooks Author app on the Mac.

00:05:15.650 --> 00:05:19.620
And they're the fastest way and the
easiest way for you to go from a concept

00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:24.210
in your head to a finished book to
something you're selling on the store.

00:05:24.430 --> 00:05:26.100
So let's take a look right now.

00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:28.770
So this is my bookshelf.

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:33.000
Not quite as extravagant as Kristi's.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.190
We're going to first look
at The Hobbit by J.R.R.

00:05:35.190 --> 00:05:36.100
Tolkien.

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:38.100
It's a flowing book.

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:41.210
When I tap on it, it opens up to the last
page I was reading,

00:05:41.210 --> 00:05:44.100
or in this case,
it's my first time opening it,

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:48.100
so it's the first page of text.

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:51.950
If I tap the page,
I can show and hide the controls.

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:57.790
If I tap on the edges of the pages,
I can actually turn the page,

00:05:57.790 --> 00:06:03.600
or we have a beautiful page curl that
tracks my finger if I want to drag.

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:08.880
Now, a flowing book is really about
making the reading experience

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:10.650
great for the customer.

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:13.480
So we've added a lot of customization.

00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:15.700
If I tap on the A's in
the top right corner,

00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:18.990
you'll see a set of customization
options for the user.

00:06:19.340 --> 00:06:21.710
I can make the text bigger.

00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:27.230
or smaller.

00:06:27.230 --> 00:06:28.180
I can even change the fonts.

00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:32.110
If I tap on the fonts button,
here's an example of Cerevec,

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:36.490
which is a really slick modern
font that we ship with the app.

00:06:39.590 --> 00:06:42.160
I'll show you a page with text.

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:45.250
Or if you prefer a more classic look,

00:06:45.610 --> 00:06:48.470
Back to the fonts menu,
I can tap on Athalos,

00:06:48.570 --> 00:06:51.130
which is a really classic
book reading font.

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:55.090
We can also change the theme.

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:58.380
So let's say you're reading in bed.

00:06:58.690 --> 00:07:00.620
And you want to get rid of the backlight.

00:07:00.870 --> 00:07:03.120
You want the text to stand out.

00:07:03.270 --> 00:07:05.320
If I tap on night mode...

00:07:06.260 --> 00:07:10.630
The page goes black and
just the text stands out.

00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:14.220
Or sepia if you like a
warmer background color.

00:07:15.370 --> 00:07:16.540
We can even go full screen.

00:07:16.540 --> 00:07:23.910
If you're the kind of reader
that wants to get rid of all

00:07:24.010 --> 00:07:26.690
the distractions on the page,
let's go into full screen mode and

00:07:26.690 --> 00:07:26.690
you'll see the book trim goes away,
and there's nothing on the

00:07:26.690 --> 00:07:26.690
page but the text itself.

00:07:27.370 --> 00:07:30.710
So of course, just like print books,
let's go to the next page,

00:07:30.710 --> 00:07:32.520
we can include images in a book.

00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:36.000
But what we can do here
that you can't do in print,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.920
if I double tap, I can actually pop that
image out of the book,

00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:45.290
zoom in and look at all the detail,
scroll around.

00:07:45.290 --> 00:07:48.480
If I double tap, it goes back.

00:07:48.480 --> 00:07:48.480
And then I can actually

00:07:49.290 --> 00:07:54.250
I can add bookmarks by tapping on the
bookmark button in the top right corner.

00:07:55.400 --> 00:07:57.350
So let's look at the table of contents.

00:07:57.550 --> 00:08:01.980
So if I go, if I tap on the table of
contents button in the top left,

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:07.720
it takes me to a page that has the entire
structure of the book under contents.

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:10.780
It also lets me view
my bookmarks and notes.

00:08:10.820 --> 00:08:14.300
Let's go take a look at a bookmark
that I've taken previously.

00:08:15.790 --> 00:08:19.800
So this takes us to a page
that has embedded audio in it.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:23.400
This is where you can
take books beyond print.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:26.150
In this case,
the publisher actually chose

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:28.380
to include clips of J.R.R.

00:08:28.430 --> 00:08:32.030
Tolkien himself singing
the songs from The Hobbit.

00:08:32.210 --> 00:08:34.700
So let's hit play and hear how it sounds.

00:08:34.700 --> 00:08:38.700
Chip the glasses and crack the blades,
blunt the knives and bend the forks.

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:43.700
That's what Bill Burbaggins hates,
smash the bottles and burn the corks.

00:08:43.800 --> 00:08:45.690
That's pretty cool.

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:46.950
If you're a Hobbit fan,
you know that the book

00:08:47.060 --> 00:08:50.280
is filled with songs,
and now you can actually understand

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:51.600
how he meant them to sound.

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:54.700
I'm not going to demo much
more on the flowing book,

00:08:54.740 --> 00:08:56.680
but I want to tell you that
there's a lot more available.

00:08:56.700 --> 00:09:00.510
So VoiceOver, for example,
iBooks is fully accessible,

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:02.620
just like the rest of the iPad.

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:08.700
Visually impaired users can have
their book read to them by the iPad,

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:11.030
but it relies on you as a content
producer to make sure that

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:15.040
you're doing things like adding
alt tags to your images or

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:17.900
closed captioning to your videos.

00:09:18.570 --> 00:09:23.220
And a couple weeks ago we
announced something great.

00:09:23.220 --> 00:09:26.110
In the last few months we've been
working on adding EPUB3 support,

00:09:26.290 --> 00:09:29.200
and we're the first reader
to announce EPUB3 support,

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:31.450
support for the new
standard inside of iBooks.

00:09:31.450 --> 00:09:34.300
Thanks.

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:38.700
So along with this comes a
number of new features as well.

00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:40.110
One of them is inline footnotes.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:42.850
So if you want to add a footnote
to your text and not take people

00:09:42.850 --> 00:09:44.550
out of their reading context,
you can do that.

00:09:44.630 --> 00:09:47.510
And you get this little pop over
that comes up and shows you the,

00:09:47.510 --> 00:09:50.800
the footnote that you want to,
to point out.

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:52.530
Or physical page numbers.

00:09:52.820 --> 00:09:56.960
So let's say I'm in class and the
teacher has assigned me The Hobbit,

00:09:56.960 --> 00:09:58.420
and she says turn to page 55.

00:09:58.420 --> 00:10:01.440
Well, it doesn't matter what font
size or font I'm reading at,

00:10:01.560 --> 00:10:08.550
I can still get to page 55 by tapping
on the search button and typing 55.

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:12.380
And we've also added the ability
to have online video and audio.

00:10:12.380 --> 00:10:16.570
So if you want to host additional
pieces of content on the Internet,

00:10:16.720 --> 00:10:20.240
you can still make those
available inside the book itself.

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:23.180
So that, that is a flowing book.

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:25.910
The next type of book I want to show you

00:10:26.470 --> 00:10:28.220
is called a fixed layout book.

00:10:28.220 --> 00:10:31.960
So let's go back to the library
and take a look at that now.

00:10:33.210 --> 00:10:37.770
So fixed layout books are perfect
when you want to start with an

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:40.370
aspect ratio or a particular layout.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:43.490
This is perfect for things
like children's books or

00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:45.380
cookbooks or picture books.

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:50.050
I'm going to tap on the second book
called Ellie's Lost and Found Sounds.

00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:55.670
So as it opens up,
you'll see some controls at the top,

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:58.100
but what's more interesting
is if you look at the page,

00:10:58.100 --> 00:11:00.880
there's actually
animations happening here.

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:03.930
Like I said,
this is completely backed by WebKit,

00:11:03.930 --> 00:11:06.640
so anything you can do
with CSS animations,

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:10.830
JavaScript, gestures and interactivity
is all available to you

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:12.640
inside of a picture book.

00:11:14.910 --> 00:11:16.300
This text is even selectable.

00:11:16.300 --> 00:11:20.000
So in this case,
the publisher included fonts

00:11:20.130 --> 00:11:21.680
with their book and shipped them.

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:26.310
If I double tap on the word "followed,"
you'll see it's actually live text.

00:11:26.650 --> 00:11:30.550
Now there's several elements on this
page that are interactive as well.

00:11:30.720 --> 00:11:34.690
So you'll see Ellie on the left here
is kind of growing and shrinking,

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:38.250
and there's a little button
that says tap to hear Ellie.

00:11:38.260 --> 00:11:39.590
So let's tap her.

00:11:39.790 --> 00:11:43.760
It's kind of a sigh or
a groan or something.

00:11:43.810 --> 00:11:50.590
On the right page there's a
few other interactive elements,

00:11:50.660 --> 00:11:52.910
so let's tap on those.

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:52.960
And they each make sounds.

00:11:56.330 --> 00:11:59.910
There's even a bee that I can drag,
and as I drag it, it makes a sound,

00:11:59.910 --> 00:12:02.690
and I can drop it off anywhere I want.

00:12:06.540 --> 00:12:08.870
So cute stuff.

00:12:09.110 --> 00:12:11.220
Now there's another feature
in Read Aloud Books,

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:13.940
sorry,
in fixed layout books called Read Aloud,

00:12:13.970 --> 00:12:17.400
that we introduced actually
right here last year at WWDC.

00:12:17.400 --> 00:12:24.990
And that allows you to include a narrated
voice along with the book that reads

00:12:24.990 --> 00:12:24.990
the words on the page to the reader.

00:12:25.420 --> 00:12:27.520
If I tap on the page to
bring up the controls,

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:29.850
you'll see an audio
button in the top right.

00:12:29.950 --> 00:12:32.300
If I tap on that, we have some options.

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:34.340
There's a big start reading button there.

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:39.740
When I tap that,
notice that each of the words are going

00:12:39.890 --> 00:12:43.810
to be lit up on the page as it's spoken.

00:12:43.810 --> 00:12:47.420
One day, Ellie followed a sound.

00:12:47.660 --> 00:12:50.570
We can scrub to another page,
and the book will

00:12:50.570 --> 00:12:50.570
actually continue reading.

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:58.010
She discovered that sounds can
be like keyholes to other worlds.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:08.920
So this is a fixed layout book.

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:12.710
There's one other thing I want to point
out about this book in particular,

00:13:12.710 --> 00:13:17.860
is that the author that created this
book actually started by building apps.

00:13:17.860 --> 00:13:21.080
And what they found is that all of
the features that they were looking

00:13:21.140 --> 00:13:25.800
for in interactivity inside an app was
available to them inside of a book.

00:13:25.830 --> 00:13:29.830
And they were having a little bit of
trouble getting noticed in the app store.

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:32.800
But as soon as they made a book
that stands out as much as this one,

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:35.280
they've become very successful with it.

00:13:35.460 --> 00:13:37.010
So back to our library.

00:13:37.170 --> 00:13:39.420
There's one last book type
that I'd like to show you,

00:13:39.510 --> 00:13:41.520
and that's a multi-touch book.

00:13:41.550 --> 00:13:46.610
Now, we launched these in January,
along with the amazing iBooks

00:13:46.610 --> 00:13:49.540
Author app that allows you to
create a book from scratch and

00:13:49.540 --> 00:13:51.500
publish it straight to the store.

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:54.240
We focus on textbooks and education.

00:13:54.270 --> 00:13:57.400
But what we've found over the
last few months is that people

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:01.460
have created some amazing things
that went beyond our expectations.

00:14:01.470 --> 00:14:05.120
This last book I'm going to
show you is "American Grown" by

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:07.660
none other than Michelle Obama.

00:14:07.660 --> 00:14:10.590
When I tap it, it opens up.

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:30.260
And it goes straight into
a beautiful intro movie.

00:14:30.260 --> 00:14:33.670
Now, when I swipe left and right
in a multi-touch book,

00:14:33.670 --> 00:14:36.670
I'm actually navigating
each of the chapters.

00:14:37.940 --> 00:14:40.230
or down at the bottom I can
swipe to get through each of the

00:14:40.230 --> 00:14:43.870
individual pages in a chapter.

00:14:43.950 --> 00:14:49.860
If I pinch on any page,
I can zoom it in to full screen.

