Identify the language of your book.

00:28:32.930 --> 00:28:36.810
If I want to read your book in Spanish,
I need to know that it's in Spanish.

00:28:36.880 --> 00:28:40.240
If I want to read in French,
I need to know that it's in French.

00:28:40.260 --> 00:28:41.080
It's that simple.

00:28:41.080 --> 00:28:44.240
Write a comprehensive
description for your book.

00:28:44.240 --> 00:28:47.900
We've talked a little bit
about this with American Grown.

00:28:47.900 --> 00:28:51.760
Definitely tell us what's there
and what makes the book special.

00:28:53.710 --> 00:28:55.530
Include target audience data.

00:28:55.640 --> 00:28:58.990
So what we mean here is that we
want you to tell us the age group

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.600
that's appropriate for the content.

00:29:01.770 --> 00:29:04.730
So there is a big
difference between Ellie,

00:29:04.730 --> 00:29:09.220
who you saw earlier,
a children's picture book, and Twilight,

00:29:09.390 --> 00:29:12.790
which is a young adult
novel about teen vampires,

00:29:12.990 --> 00:29:16.580
and I think everyone's
pretty familiar with that.

00:29:16.650 --> 00:29:18.170
You know,
make sure that as we're merchandising,

00:29:18.170 --> 00:29:18.170
we know what kind of book you've sent us.

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:20.840
Provide series detail.

00:29:20.840 --> 00:29:24.060
If you're writing books in a series,
make sure that I know where to start,

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:25.780
that I know the order of the series.

00:29:25.780 --> 00:29:28.880
I would have been pretty disappointed
if I had started with Sookie

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:31.610
Stockhouse book number four,
because a lot of surprises

00:29:31.610 --> 00:29:33.310
would have been ruined for me.

00:29:33.310 --> 00:29:36.430
Make sure that you're telling us
about your series information.

00:29:36.430 --> 00:29:40.580
And finally, proofread everything
before you send it to us.

00:29:40.580 --> 00:29:45.350
Make sure that that data is flawless,
because you want to be beautifully

00:29:45.350 --> 00:29:47.440
represented in the store.

00:29:48.820 --> 00:29:51.200
And that's metadata.

00:29:51.780 --> 00:29:54.060
So let's talk about images,
marketing image.

00:29:54.180 --> 00:29:56.990
This is the front cover
image of your book,

00:29:56.990 --> 00:29:59.470
and it's required for
delivery to the store.

00:29:59.630 --> 00:30:01.680
So you have to send us one of these.

00:30:01.710 --> 00:30:04.770
Now, there are some technical
specifications for this,

00:30:04.940 --> 00:30:08.640
specific file types and sizes
that you need to adhere to.

00:30:08.680 --> 00:30:11.930
But what I want to make sure that
you're thinking about is having

00:30:11.930 --> 00:30:15.720
a really attention-grabbing,
beautiful cover for your book.

00:30:15.750 --> 00:30:18.540
When I'm going through the search
results in the iBookstore as a reader,

00:30:18.540 --> 00:30:20.910
and I'm thinking about
what I want to read next,

00:30:21.130 --> 00:30:22.760
grab me with your art.

00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:27.900
Make me want to go into that product
page and see what your book has to offer.

00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:30.200
And again, screenshots.

00:30:30.240 --> 00:30:32.230
You need to take
advantage of screenshots.

00:30:32.500 --> 00:30:36.010
These are fantastic for
highly illustrated text.

00:30:36.140 --> 00:30:39.230
You can give us up to five per book,
and you can order them

00:30:39.230 --> 00:30:40.220
any way you'd like.

00:30:40.220 --> 00:30:43.700
So you can tell us the story of
the book and bring your reader in.

00:30:43.970 --> 00:30:47.880
Draw them in by telling them
the story with screenshots.

00:30:49.700 --> 00:30:51.930
And finally, you need to give us a book.

00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:55.810
It would be a little bit hard for someone
to read your book if we didn't have it.

00:30:55.990 --> 00:30:59.320
We work with two file
formats in the iBook store,

00:30:59.320 --> 00:31:01.860
and I'll show you both
of those earlier today.

00:31:01.860 --> 00:31:05.170
First, we have multi-touch books,
and these are books

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:06.440
created with iBooks Author.

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:10.140
Second, we have EPUB, including EPUB 3.

00:31:10.140 --> 00:31:13.840
Now, as you're designing your books,
you're going to be using those creation

00:31:13.940 --> 00:31:17.120
tools that we talked about earlier,
but you need to bring a strong

00:31:17.120 --> 00:31:19.200
editorial eye to your content.

00:31:19.200 --> 00:31:21.050
I mean,
what kind of book are you writing?

00:31:21.060 --> 00:31:24.100
If you're writing a novel,
maybe an EPUB flowing

00:31:24.270 --> 00:31:26.080
book is perfect for you.

00:31:26.080 --> 00:31:29.400
But if you're creating a
highly interactive textbook,

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:32.830
chances are you need the widgets
offered by iBooks Author,

00:31:32.960 --> 00:31:35.480
and you'll want to use
that to create your book.

00:31:35.580 --> 00:31:41.460
Now, we believe that book creation and
design is such a deep topic that we've

00:31:41.460 --> 00:31:45.570
dedicated four additional sessions
at this year's conference to it.

00:31:45.730 --> 00:31:48.580
So we'll talk a little bit about
those at the end of the session,

00:31:48.580 --> 00:31:51.910
but I just want to mention, now, I mean,
this is not all that you're going to

00:31:51.910 --> 00:31:53.800
get in the world of book creation.

00:31:53.820 --> 00:31:58.710
So once you've got everything together,
you've built your package, please test.

00:31:58.800 --> 00:31:59.770
You guys are developers.

00:31:59.780 --> 00:32:02.880
I know you know how to test things
before you deliver them to us,

00:32:02.960 --> 00:32:06.170
but we wanted to focus a little
bit on some of the best practices

00:32:06.260 --> 00:32:09.960
we can recommend for testing books
before you deliver them to the store.

00:32:09.960 --> 00:32:13.590
So first, test on devices.

00:32:13.600 --> 00:32:17.080
You want to make sure, you know,
take a walk in that reader's shoes.

00:32:17.080 --> 00:32:19.540
Make sure the book functions as intended.

00:32:19.540 --> 00:32:24.080
Make sure that you're looking at it
from both the portrait orientation

00:32:24.210 --> 00:32:28.010
and also the landscape orientation,
so that as your reader,

00:32:28.010 --> 00:32:31.900
I have a great experience regardless
of how I like to use my device.

00:32:32.080 --> 00:32:37.330
Use BookProofer to test your EPUBs,
and also look at iBooks Author's

00:32:37.330 --> 00:32:39.580
preview feature for multi-touch books.

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:43.360
Take advantage of the tools we
give you so that testing is easy.

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:49.040
If you need to make a change to a
file after you've delivered it to us,

00:32:49.180 --> 00:32:50.640
please do regression testing.

00:32:50.640 --> 00:32:52.880
I mean, I know you guys do this
every day with your apps.

00:32:53.030 --> 00:32:55.140
It's really no different from books.

00:32:55.220 --> 00:32:57.470
If you make a change
in part A of your book,

00:32:57.740 --> 00:33:01.590
make certain that you didn't break
something further down the line.

00:33:01.690 --> 00:33:05.800
And finally,
think about navigation for books.

00:33:05.880 --> 00:33:08.990
There is a table of
contents feature in iBooks.

00:33:09.070 --> 00:33:12.920
You need to make sure that your book
is constructed so that as a reader,

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:15.120
I'm able to easily navigate
through your content.

00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:17.830
Also, make sure your links work.

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:19.810
Don't take me to a dead end.

00:33:19.910 --> 00:33:22.260
It's really that simple.

00:33:22.260 --> 00:33:25.180
You always, always need to develop
with your reader in mind.

00:33:25.180 --> 00:33:28.400
So today,
we wanted to give you a few of our

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:31.180
recommendations for how you can do that.

00:33:31.660 --> 00:33:33.180
Beginning with accessibility.

00:33:33.720 --> 00:33:40.310
Both the iOS and iBooks have a
ton of features to enable really

00:33:40.320 --> 00:33:45.060
accessible content on Apple devices.

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:45.160
You should make sure that anyone
who wants to read your book

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:45.160
has the ability to do that.

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:49.010
The iBooks or asset guide talks a
lot about EPUB and how you can make

00:33:49.010 --> 00:33:51.100
sure your EPUBs are accessible.

00:33:51.220 --> 00:33:55.200
iBooks author comes with built-in
options to allow you to create accessible

00:33:55.280 --> 00:33:57.160
features in a multi-touch book.

00:33:57.160 --> 00:33:59.080
Take advantage of this.

00:33:59.140 --> 00:34:00.990
File size.

00:34:00.990 --> 00:34:04.280
So your books can be up
to two gigabytes in size.

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:09.120
But just because you can do it doesn't
necessarily mean that you should.

00:34:09.120 --> 00:34:12.900
As you're adding video, audio,
sort of heavy elements,

00:34:12.900 --> 00:34:15.140
really take a strong editorial approach.

00:34:15.140 --> 00:34:18.380
You don't want to be a blind eye to
whether they really make the book.

00:34:18.380 --> 00:34:21.980
Because you don't know where someone's
going to be downloading that book.

00:34:21.980 --> 00:34:24.050
They may not have a fantastic connection.

00:34:24.130 --> 00:34:28.050
Really think about file size and think
about your reader as you build your book.

00:34:28.160 --> 00:34:28.870
Fingers.

00:34:28.870 --> 00:34:31.620
So it may seem strange
to see fingers up here.

00:34:31.620 --> 00:34:34.170
But this goes back to interactive books.

00:34:34.170 --> 00:34:38.470
Now, if I'm a child who just got Ellie,
you know, my motor skills may not

00:34:38.540 --> 00:34:40.020
be as developed as ours.

00:34:40.030 --> 00:34:44.200
So think about that as you're
designing hot zones for your books.

00:34:45.120 --> 00:34:46.120
Length.

00:34:46.120 --> 00:34:47.120
Length should work.

00:34:47.120 --> 00:34:48.230
That's really -- that's it.

00:34:48.340 --> 00:34:50.120
Speed.

00:34:50.120 --> 00:34:54.320
The iBooks or asset guide offers a
lot of guidance about how you can

00:34:54.320 --> 00:34:58.980
have a book that performs really
efficiently and quickly on the device.

00:34:59.270 --> 00:35:01.700
Make sure that you're taking
advantage of all of those places

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:03.140
to improve book performance.

00:35:03.140 --> 00:35:06.810
It can be as simple as
substituting a JPEG for a PNG.

00:35:07.080 --> 00:35:09.140
It can be really that easy.

00:35:09.140 --> 00:35:10.660
Text.

00:35:11.380 --> 00:35:14.850
They're books.

00:35:15.080 --> 00:35:15.100
We get a lot of complaints when
books have misspelled words.

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:16.400
Or bad grammar.

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:19.490
Or maybe the text is
overlapping on pages.

00:35:19.980 --> 00:35:22.890
Your QC process and your
development process needs to

00:35:23.030 --> 00:35:25.070
be really focused on the text.

00:35:25.080 --> 00:35:28.050
And finally, zoom.

00:35:28.270 --> 00:35:29.930
This is about image quality.

00:35:30.280 --> 00:35:33.440
Our devices are capable of
rendering art beautifully.

00:35:33.900 --> 00:35:36.170
Make sure that when someone's
pinching and zooming,

00:35:36.170 --> 00:35:40.910
as Al showed you, that the image doesn't
become blurry or pixelated.

00:35:40.910 --> 00:35:44.590
Make sure that your reader is having
a really great experience with images.

00:35:46.210 --> 00:35:49.060
So once you deliver your book to us,
you've gone through all of these steps,

00:35:49.150 --> 00:35:50.940
you've thought carefully
about your reader,

00:35:50.940 --> 00:35:53.600
your book will go through
quality control at Apple.

00:35:53.600 --> 00:35:55.700
Every book goes through review.

00:35:55.700 --> 00:35:58.000
And it's a pretty simple process.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:35:59.540
We put the book on an iPad.

00:35:59.540 --> 00:36:01.060
We test it.

00:36:01.130 --> 00:36:03.140
If you have widgets,
we're going to test them.

00:36:03.140 --> 00:36:04.220
We're going to make sure that they work.

00:36:04.310 --> 00:36:07.720
If we find anything wrong,
we'll issue a ticket to you.

00:36:07.720 --> 00:36:09.360
You can get tickets by email.

00:36:09.360 --> 00:36:11.980
You can also access
them in iTunes Connect,

00:36:11.980 --> 00:36:13.740
as you see here in step two.

00:36:14.220 --> 00:36:17.150
There's a ticket history module that
will list out all of this information.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:20.800
If something goes wrong,
all you need to do to get

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:23.680
yourself back in a review queue
is to re-deliver the book.

00:36:23.800 --> 00:36:26.950
And again,
make sure you've tested the book again

00:36:27.370 --> 00:36:29.580
end-to-end before you re-submit to us.

00:36:29.720 --> 00:36:33.270
When it comes back in,
we're going to put it on an iPad again.

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:34.240
We'll check it out.

00:36:34.420 --> 00:36:37.980
If everything's okay,
it goes right out to the store for sale,

00:36:37.980 --> 00:36:40.240
as you see pictured here in step four.

00:36:42.240 --> 00:36:44.620
Now,
thinking about the book approval process,

00:36:44.620 --> 00:36:47.860
it seems only fitting that we should
share with you some of the top

00:36:47.860 --> 00:36:49.720
reasons why we see books rejected.

00:36:49.890 --> 00:36:54.140
We really wanted to make sure that we
gave you guys some great best practices.

00:36:54.140 --> 00:36:59.990
One, omitting the custom preview from
multi-touch books and read-allowed books.

00:36:59.990 --> 00:37:03.230
Some of our more complex formats
require our book partners to

00:37:03.330 --> 00:37:06.680
provide the sample that the
customer receives from the store.

00:37:07.410 --> 00:37:10.230
Two, making sure that you're looking
at the requirements in the asset

00:37:10.340 --> 00:37:12.700
guide and that if you need to
deliver one of these books,

00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:16.010
make sure you're providing a sample.

00:37:16.510 --> 00:37:18.930
Book image is larger
than 2 million pixels.

00:37:19.060 --> 00:37:22.380
So Al touched a little
bit about WebKit and how

00:37:22.380 --> 00:37:24.780
WebKit interacts with iBooks.

00:37:25.120 --> 00:37:27.530
To make sure that your
book functions correctly,

00:37:27.770 --> 00:37:30.810
we need to make sure that the
interior images of the book are

00:37:30.810 --> 00:37:32.800
smaller than 2 million pixels.

00:37:32.900 --> 00:37:38.220
If you send in images larger than that,
we'll actually reject them

00:37:38.220 --> 00:37:38.220
at the time of delivery.

00:37:38.940 --> 00:37:40.980
and complete table of contents.

00:37:41.010 --> 00:37:43.480
Again, book navigation is key.

00:37:43.520 --> 00:37:46.820
If there are 50 chapters in the book,
make sure that the table of

00:37:46.820 --> 00:37:48.860
contents shows me 50 chapters.

00:37:48.930 --> 00:37:50.620
Don't just give me one or two.

00:37:50.660 --> 00:37:55.150
As a reader, I'm going to be pretty
dissatisfied with that experience.

00:37:55.780 --> 00:37:59.210
Incorrect subject or
classification schema.

00:37:59.570 --> 00:38:02.520
Well, you'll see a little bit more
about this in a few moments.

00:38:02.520 --> 00:38:04.940
But again, help us merchandise your book.

00:38:04.940 --> 00:38:11.890
If it's a cookbook,
tell us it's a cookbook.

00:38:11.890 --> 00:38:11.890
If it's a sci-fi novel,
tell us it's a sci-fi novel.

00:38:13.260 --> 00:38:14.270
Poor image quality.

00:38:14.580 --> 00:38:15.840
We've touched about this a little bit.

00:38:16.040 --> 00:38:18.500
Make sure your images look great.

00:38:18.630 --> 00:38:19.890
Misusing Apple trademarks.

00:38:20.050 --> 00:38:21.640
I mean, this is pretty simple.

00:38:21.640 --> 00:38:27.490
Just make sure you're aware of the rules
for using any Apple trademarked names.

00:38:27.660 --> 00:38:29.020
Compound authors and metadata.

00:38:29.070 --> 00:38:30.220
This is a really common one.

00:38:30.350 --> 00:38:32.310
So if Al and I were to
write a book together,

00:38:32.480 --> 00:38:34.970
the author wouldn't be Kristi
and Al smushed together in

00:38:34.970 --> 00:38:36.540
one field in the metadata.

00:38:36.570 --> 00:38:39.360
I should get my own billing,
and Al should get his own.

00:38:39.390 --> 00:38:44.360
You want to make sure that you tell us
who contributed to that work clearly.

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:45.480
Asset mismatch.

00:38:45.480 --> 00:38:47.220
This is pretty simple as well.

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:49.110
Make sure that the
jacket that you give us,

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:53.450
the marketing image you give us,
matches the book file itself.

00:38:54.630 --> 00:38:55.720
False advertising.

00:38:55.980 --> 00:38:58.030
Don't promise the reader something
they're not going to get.

00:38:58.270 --> 00:39:00.890
They get upset by that,
and it results in customer

00:39:00.890 --> 00:39:03.000
complaints and sometimes refunds.

00:39:03.140 --> 00:39:06.560
So you want to make certain that you
give them exactly what you've promised.

00:39:06.640 --> 00:39:09.220
And finally,
incorrect language and metadata.

00:39:09.220 --> 00:39:12.640
We've talked a lot about language,
but the iBookstore is global.

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:15.610
We need to know what language
that book is prepared in.

00:39:15.620 --> 00:39:19.090
So this is a lot to take in,
and what we wanted to do

00:39:19.090 --> 00:39:23.330
this morning is show you just
how to put it into practice.

00:39:24.250 --> 00:39:27.100
So to do that,
I'd like to introduce Ryan Lynch,

00:39:27.150 --> 00:39:29.620
our global operations
manager for the iBookstore,

00:39:29.710 --> 00:39:31.680
and he's going to take us
through delivering a book.

00:39:31.680 --> 00:39:33.410
Thank you, Kristi.

00:39:33.500 --> 00:39:37.010
So I'm going to talk about delivering
and managing your books in the

00:39:37.010 --> 00:39:41.920
iBookstore with our two tools,
iTunes Producer,

00:39:42.090 --> 00:39:46.070
an OSX app for managing delivery,
and then iTunes Connect,

00:39:46.070 --> 00:39:50.410
which I think most of you are already
familiar with for managing your content

00:39:50.490 --> 00:39:52.930
after you've delivered it to us.

00:39:53.290 --> 00:39:56.360
So first, iTunes Producer.

00:39:56.450 --> 00:40:00.110
So I've already loaded
it up here on my Mac.

00:40:00.690 --> 00:40:06.660
And you'll notice here that I've got four
main options for creating my content.

00:40:06.780 --> 00:40:09.200
The first is opening a package.

00:40:09.300 --> 00:40:09.900
So I'd do that.

00:40:09.900 --> 00:40:16.590
I'd open a book that I've already created
or already delivered so that I can

00:40:16.590 --> 00:40:16.590
update it and re-deliver it to the store.

00:40:16.970 --> 00:40:20.860
The second is I can create a new
package or a new book from scratch.

00:40:20.860 --> 00:40:24.720
So I can do that either one at
a time with the new book or,

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:27.550
on the other side, new from a file.

00:40:27.560 --> 00:40:31.510
So iTunes Producer gives you
the ability to deliver 10,

00:40:31.510 --> 00:40:36.300
20, 50 books at the same time if
you want via a spreadsheet.

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:41.450
And that is available in the
File menu of iTunes Producer.

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:44.560
I'm not going to walk you
through that right now,

00:40:44.660 --> 00:40:48.190
but if you do choose this path,
be sure that you fill it out

00:40:48.190 --> 00:40:52.650
completely and exactly as it is
demoed in the sample document.

00:40:55.570 --> 00:40:58.490
The last option is looking up metadata.

00:40:58.610 --> 00:41:01.810
So if you've already delivered
a book to the bookstore,

00:41:01.810 --> 00:41:06.050
you can use your Apple ID,
which is the identifier of

00:41:06.050 --> 00:41:10.090
the book that we assign,
your vendor ID or ISBN.

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:12.940
You put it in here,
it'll pull down a metadata that

00:41:12.940 --> 00:41:14.770
we actually have on the server.

00:41:14.850 --> 00:41:18.660
You can make updates and
then re-deliver that to us.

00:41:19.110 --> 00:41:22.000
For the purposes of this demo,
I'm going to open a package

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:24.310
that I've already created.

